'''''Omni-Play Horse Racing''''' is a 1989 video game published by [[SportTime]].

==Gameplay==
''Omni-Play Horse Racing'' is a game in which a horse racing system is featured with 128 horses in its database.<ref name="CGW64"/>

==Reception==
Johnny L. Wilson reviewed the game for ''[[Computer Gaming World]]'', and stated that "''Omni-Play Horse Racing'' is an excellent simulation of the Sport of Kings. The number of variables factored into each race and the entertainment value provided put this product into the 'Winner's Circle"."<ref name="CGW64">{{cite magazine |last=Wilson |first=Johnny L. |title=And . . . . They're Off!: Sport Time's "Omni-Play Horse Racing" |magazine=Computer Gaming World |date=October 1989 |volume=1 |issue=64 |pages=49–52}}</ref>

Brian Walker reviewed ''Omni-Play Horse Racing'' and ''[[A Day at the Races (video game)|A Day at the Races]]'' for ''[[Games International]]'' magazine, and gave it a rating of 10 out of 10, and stated that "if stable management is your game then ''HR'' just shades it over ''ADAR''."<ref name="gi15">{{cite journal | last = Walker |first = Brian | title =Friends of the Turf: Computer Games | journal = [[Games International]] | issue = 15 | pages =20–21 |date=June 1990}}</ref>

